# Mobile App Authentication

This guide covers connecting mobile apps and headless devices to Nocturne using the
OAuth 2.0 Device Authorization Grant ([RFC 8628](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8628)).
For web apps or desktop apps that can open a browser, see the
[Authorization Code + PKCE guide](/docs/connecting-apps).

Nocturne uses the Device Authorization flow for apps that either can't easily open a
redirect-based browser flow or run on devices with limited input. The user authorizes
on a separate device (phone, computer) by entering a short code.

## 1. Register your app

Before your app can authenticate users, it needs a `client_id`. Nocturne supports
[Dynamic Client Registration (RFC 7591)](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc7591) —
your app registers itself by calling a single endpoint.

```typescript
const response = await fetch(
  "https://your-nocturne-instance.com/api/oauth/register",
  {
    method: "POST",
    headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
    body: JSON.stringify({
      client_name: "My Diabetes App",
      software_id: "org.example.mydiabetesapp",
      redirect_uris: ["org.example.mydiabetesapp://oauth/callback"],
    }),
  }
);

const { client_id } = await response.json();
```

Registration is **idempotent per tenant** — if your `software_id` is already registered
on that Nocturne instance, you'll get the existing `client_id` back. Store the `client_id`;
you'll need it for every authorization request.

<Callout type="info" title="Well-known apps">
  Popular diabetes apps (Trio, xDrip+, Loop, AAPS) are pre-registered on every Nocturne
  instance. Calling register with their <code>software_id</code> returns the existing
  <code>client_id</code> without creating a duplicate.
</Callout>

## 2. Start device authorization

Request a device code by calling the device authorization endpoint with your `client_id`
and the scopes your app needs:

```typescript
const deviceResponse = await fetch(
  "https://your-nocturne-instance.com/api/oauth/device",
  {
    method: "POST",
    headers: { "Content-Type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded" },
    body: new URLSearchParams({
      client_id: clientId,
      scope: "entries.readwrite heartrate.readwrite stepcount.readwrite",
    }),
  }
);

const {
  device_code,
  user_code,
  verification_uri,
  verification_uri_complete,
  expires_in,
  interval,
} = await deviceResponse.json();
```

The response contains everything you need to guide the user through authorization:

- **`user_code`** — a short alphanumeric code like `BCTV-3KMN` the user enters
- **`verification_uri`** — where the user goes to enter the code
- **`verification_uri_complete`** — has the code pre-filled (use this for "Open in browser" buttons)
- **`expires_in`** — how long the code is valid (30 minutes)
- **`interval`** — minimum polling interval in seconds (5 seconds)

## 3. Display the code to the user

Show the `user_code` prominently in your app. If possible, offer a button that opens
`verification_uri_complete` in a browser — the code is pre-filled so the user just
needs to sign in and approve.

## 4. Poll for the token

While the user is authorizing on their other device, poll the token endpoint every
`interval` seconds. The server will tell you when the user has approved (or denied)
the request.

```typescript
async function pollForToken(
  baseUrl: string,
  clientId: string,
  deviceCode: string,
  intervalSeconds: number,
): Promise<{ access_token: string; refresh_token: string }> {
  let currentInterval = intervalSeconds;

  while (true) {
    await new Promise((resolve) => setTimeout(resolve, currentInterval * 1000));

    const response = await fetch(`${baseUrl}/api/oauth/token`, {
      method: "POST",
      headers: { "Content-Type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded" },
      body: new URLSearchParams({
        grant_type: "urn:ietf:params:oauth:grant-type:device_code",
        device_code: deviceCode,
        client_id: clientId,
      }),
    });

    const data = await response.json();

    if (response.ok) {
      return data; // { access_token, refresh_token, expires_in, token_type }
    }

    switch (data.error) {
      case "authorization_pending":
        continue;
      case "slow_down":
        currentInterval += 5;
        continue;
      case "expired_token":
        throw new Error("Device code expired. Please restart the authorization.");
      case "access_denied":
        throw new Error("Authorization denied by user.");
      default:
        throw new Error(`Unexpected error: ${data.error}`);
    }
  }
}
```

<Callout type="warning" title="Store tokens securely">
  The refresh token is long-lived and grants ongoing access. Store it in your
  platform's secure storage (Keychain on iOS, EncryptedSharedPreferences on Android,
  or an encrypted store on desktop). Never store tokens in plain text.
</Callout>

## 5. Make API calls

Use the access token as a Bearer token in the `Authorization` header:

```typescript
const entries = await fetch(
  "https://your-nocturne-instance.com/api/v4/glucose/sensor",
  {
    headers: {
      Authorization: `Bearer ${accessToken}`,
    },
  }
);
```

If the token has expired, the API returns `401 Unauthorized`. If the token lacks the
required scope for an endpoint, you'll get `403 Forbidden`.

## 6. Refresh tokens

Access tokens expire (check the `expires_in` value from the token response). When one
expires, use the refresh token to get a new pair:

```typescript
const refreshResponse = await fetch(
  "https://your-nocturne-instance.com/api/oauth/token",
  {
    method: "POST",
    headers: { "Content-Type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded" },
    body: new URLSearchParams({
      grant_type: "refresh_token",
      refresh_token: storedRefreshToken,
      client_id: clientId,
    }),
  }
);

const { access_token, refresh_token } = await refreshResponse.json();
// Store BOTH new tokens — the old refresh token is now invalid
```

<Callout type="danger" title="Refresh tokens rotate">
  Each refresh returns a <strong>new</strong> refresh token and invalidates the old one.
  Always store the latest refresh token. If you replay an old refresh token,
  the entire grant is revoked for security and the user will need to re-authorize.
</Callout>

## 7. Revoking access

When the user signs out or disconnects your app, revoke the token:

```typescript
await fetch("https://your-nocturne-instance.com/api/oauth/revoke", {
  method: "POST",
  headers: { "Content-Type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded" },
  body: new URLSearchParams({
    token: refreshToken,
    token_type_hint: "refresh_token",
    client_id: clientId,
  }),
});
```

Users can also revoke your app's access from their Nocturne settings at any time.

## Scopes

Scopes control what your app can access. Request only what you need.

| Scope | Access |
|-------|--------|
| `entries.read` | Read glucose readings |
| `entries.readwrite` | Read and write glucose readings |
| `treatments.read` | Read treatments (insulin, carbs, notes) |
| `treatments.readwrite` | Read and write treatments |
| `devicestatus.read` | Read pump and CGM device status |
| `devicestatus.readwrite` | Read and write device status |
| `profile.read` | Read user profile and settings |
| `profile.readwrite` | Read and write profile |
| `heartrate.read` | Read heart rate data |
| `heartrate.readwrite` | Read and write heart rate data |
| `stepcount.read` | Read step count data |
| `stepcount.readwrite` | Read and write step count data |
| `notifications.read` | Read notifications |
| `notifications.readwrite` | Read and write notifications |
| `reports.read` | Read reports |
| `identity.read` | Read account identity |
| `sharing.readwrite` | Manage sharing settings |
| `health.read` | Shorthand for all `.read` health scopes |
| `health.readwrite` | Shorthand for all `.readwrite` health scopes |
| `*` | Full access (use sparingly) |

A `readwrite` scope always implies `read` — you don't need to request both.

<Callout type="info" title="Scope expansion">
  <code>health.read</code> and <code>health.readwrite</code> are convenience aliases.
  When you request them, the consent screen shows the individual scopes they expand to.
</Callout>
